<div id="tmglBody" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Article">
	<div class="access"><a name="article"></a></div>

	<div class="twoThirdsThird2 gutterUnder">
		<div class="twoThirds gutter">
			<script type="text/javascript" src="/web/20181117040851js_/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/template/ver1-0/js/jquery-ui.js"></script>
<script type="text/javascript" src="/web/20181117040851js_/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/template/ver1-0/js/jquery.multiselect.js"></script>

<div class="storyHead">

<h1 itemprop="headline name">The man with the golden tongue</h1>
			<!-- Opta Widget start -->
	<!-- Opta Widget end -->
	
	</div>
<div class="oneHalf gutter">
								<div class="story">
		<div class="cl"> </div>
		<div class="byline">
		<div>

			<p class="bylineBody"><span itemprop="author"> By Andrew Roberts</span></p>
				</div>
		<p class="publishedDate">12:00AM GMT 28 Jan 2001</p>
		<meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2001-01-28"/><div class="cl"> </div>
	</div>
	<div id="mainBodyArea" itemprop="articleBody">

	<div class="firstPar"><p>RICHARD Tomlinson and I were born on the same day and went to the same Cambridge college together. He was a bright and charming undergraduate, popular with the boys for his drinking and sporting prowess, and with the girls for his dark good looks. If there was something exaggerated about his tales about himself - a slight Walter Mitty complex - it hardly mattered in the relaxed and tolerant environment of university life. Neither did his obvious and driving ambition seem particularly untoward.</p></div><div class="secondPar"><p>Richard and I both took firsts and were years later both approached to join MI6. I passed all the (often hilarious) entry procedures, but decided after completing them to write history books instead. Richard went ahead and spent four years in "Six". There the fatal combination of his ambition and his fantasising soon emerged to threaten what must at the outset have seemed a very promising career.</p></div><div class="thirdPar"><p>Integral to the success of a spy is his anonymity; however high he gets in the service he does not received the honours, job titles, and so on, that he might have received elsewhere in the civil service. Richard, a man for whom public recognition of his talents meant a lot, did not really understand that. Furthermore the temptation to believe that he personified that other tall, dark, handsome Cambridge-educated masterspy, James Bond, soon proved overwhelming. In "Six" they call it "the 007 complex", and according to some of our Cambridge contemporaries, Richard suffered from an acute case of it.</p></div><div class="fourthPar"><p>Friends who heard his tales of behind-the-lines tradecraft in war-torn Bosnia - complete with satellite phones, pen-guns and beautiful local girls - recall looking at one another with amusement before humming the Live and Let Die theme tune to tease him. Only - unlike at university - this time he didn't smile.</p></div><div class="fifthPar"><p>Since his sacking by MI6 in 1995, his stories have grown more and more absurd. He now admits having made up the disgusting lie that MI6 was involved in the "assassination" of the late Diana, Princess of Wales. Richard has consistently manipulated the truth to serve his emotions and vendettas, with this newspaper (and its editor) as a regular target because it has consistently pointed out the self-serving inaccuracies and inconsistencies in his claims. In his book he accuses me of "making absurd claims" in an earlier article I wrote about him. To be accused by Richard Tomlinson of "making absurd claims" must qualify as some kind of triumph.</p></div><div class="body"><p>Richard needed to write a book not just for the cash but also because of his gargantuan appetite for publicity. It was a noticeable but by no means pathological trait at university; now he will say literally anything to embarrass his former colleagues, boost his book's sales and, above all, stay in the news. When I last wrote about Richard, I received an angry, anguished letter from his mother. This newspaper had run an article by me about Richard's wild drugs-and-motorbikes post-Cambridge way of life, complete with a photograph of him dressed as a transvestite at the 1995 Gay Pride march (taken when he was still a serving MI6 officer).</p><p>Reading between the lines of his mother's letter, I felt that although she probably privately disapproved of Richard's treachery, her maternal instincts had prevailed and she and her husband publicly supported him. It was a moving, highly intelligent, pained letter, and I hope my reply convinced her that there was nothing personal in my attack on her son, merely the normal reaction of someone who has seen his country and the reputation of his college betrayed.</p><p>If Richard had not been so ambitious he might not have overreacted so badly when MI6 sacked him. Yet his amour-propre was hurt by his rejection, and he decided to do whatever it took to damage his former employers. His publication of the names of 115 alleged MI6 officers, with comments about each, was a particularly vicious action, putting the lives of many of his former colleagues in jeopardy.</p><p>The last time I wrote about Richard, I received a visit at home from two gentlemen from Special Branch who said that he had requested that I be investigated for breaking the Official Secrets Act, which, like Richard, I had also signed when undergoing positive vetting. I was subsequently cleared, and a little later one of the policemen summed up the situation perfectly when he told me: "We don't think Tomlinson is blowing the whistle, so much as his own trumpet."</p></div><div class="cl"></div>
</div>

</div></div>
		
							<div class="oneSixth">
									<!-- googleoff: all -->

